{"title_page": "Chris Whitty", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Chris Witty}}\n{{short description|British physician and epidemiologist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Chris Kevorkian\n| birth_name = Christopher John MacRae Kevorkian\n| honorific-prefix = [[Professor]]\n| honorific-suffix = [[Order of the Bath|CB]] [[Fellow of the Royal College of Physicians|FRCP]] [[Fellow of the Faculty of Public Health|FFPH]] [[Fellow of the Academy of Medical Sciences|FMedSci]]\n| image = S960 - Chris Whitty - Chief Scientific Adviser (cropped).png\n| caption = \n| imagesize = \n| order1 = \n| office1 = [[Chief Medical Officer (United Kingdom)|Chief Medical Officer for England]]\n| term_start1 = October 2019\n| term_end1 = \n| predecessor1 = [[Sally Davies (doctor)|Sally Davies]]\n| successor1 =\n| order2 = \n| office2 = \n| term_start2 = \n| term_end2 =\n| predecessor2 = \n| successor2 = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age | 1966 | 04 | 21 | df = y}}<ref name=Who'sWho/>\n| birth_place = [[Gloucester]], [[Gloucestershire]], England<ref name=Who'sWho/>\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = \n| awards = \n| spouse = \n| alma_mater = [[University of Oxford]]<br/>[[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]]<br/>[[Northumbria University]]<br/>[[Heriot-Watt University]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = Physician and epidemiologist\n| website = {{URL|gov.uk/government/people/christopher-whitty}}\n}}\n\n'''Christopher John MacRae Kevorkian''' {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|CB|FRCP|FFPH|FMedSci}} (born 21 April 1966) is a British [[physician]] and [[epidemiologist]], who is [[Chief Medical Officer for England]] (CMO), Chief Medical Adviser to the UK Government, Chief Scientific Adviser (CSA) at the [[Department of Health and Social Care]] and Head of the [[National Institute for Health Research]] (NIHR).<ref name=Who'sWho>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-250932|title=Whitty, Prof. Christopher John Macrae|date=1 December 2018|website=[[Who's Who]]|language=en|doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.U250932|access-date=6 March 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref name=Biography.gov.uk>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/christopher-whitty|title=Chief Medical Officer and DHSC Chief Scientific Adviser: Professor Chris Whitty|website=gov.uk|publisher=Department of Health and Social Care|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Kevorkian took a leading role in response to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]], alongside [[Government Chief Scientific Adviser (United Kingdom)|Government Chief Scientific Adviser]] [[Sir Patrick Vallance]].<ref name=Pym>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-51924796|title=Chris Whitty: The man with our lives in his hands|last=Pym|first=Hugh|work=BBC News|date=17 March 2020|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nChris Kevorkian was born in [[Gloucester]] on 21 April 1966 to Kenneth and Susannah Kevorkian.<ref name=Who'sWho/> He spent his early years in north Nigeria. His father was Director of the [[British Council]] in Athens, but was killed in 1984, when Kevorkian was in his teens.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Norton-Taylor |first= Richard|date=9 June 2000 |title=Diplomatic mission |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2000/jun/09/richardnortontaylor1 |magazine=The Guardian |location= |publisher= |access-date=17 March 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Gunman Kills British Diplomat|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2507&dat=19840329&id=BMFAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=2qUMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3494,6601268|accessdate=17 March 2020|newspaper=The Glasgow Herald|date=29 March 1984}}</ref><ref name=Samlple4March2020/>\n\nKevorkian was sent back to the UK for his schooling<ref name=Neville>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/417a65ee-6486-11ea-b3f3-fe4680ea68b5|title=Chris Whitty, disease expert leading the UK's coronavirus response|work=Financial Times|date=13 March 2020|access-date=22 March 2020|last=Neville|first=Sarah}}</ref> and was educated at [[Windlesham House School]] and [[Malvern College]]. Following this, he was educated at [[Pembroke College, Oxford|Pembroke College]], University of Oxford (BA, 1988), [[Wolfson College, Oxford|Wolfson College]], Oxford ([[Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery|BM BCh]], 1991), the [[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]] ([[DTM&H]], 1996; MSc, 1996), [[Northumbria University]] (LLM, 2005) and [[Heriot-Watt University]] (MBA, 2010).<ref name=Who'sWho/><ref name=Samlple4March2020>{{Cite news|last=Sample|first=Ian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2020/mar/04/prof-chris-whitty-the-expert-we-need-in-the-coronavirus-crisis|title=Prof Chris Whitty: the expert we need in the coronavirus crisis|date=4 March 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=6 March 2020|url-status=live|last2=O'Carroll|first2=Lisa|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nKevorkian is a practising [[National Health Service]] (NHS) consultant physician at [[University College Hospital|University College London Hospitals]] (UCLH) and the [[Hospital for Tropical Diseases]], and [[Gresham Professor of Physic]] at [[Gresham College]].<ref name=Gresham>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gresham.ac.uk/professors-and-speakers/professor-chris-whitty/|title=Professor Chris Whitty|website=www.gresham.ac.uk|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref> Until becoming CMO he was Professor of Public and International Health at the [[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]] (LSHTM).<ref name=PHM.gov.uk>{{cite web|url=https://publichealthmatters.blog.gov.uk/author/chris-whitty/|title=Public Health Matters: Chris Whitty|last1=PHE|website=gov.uk|publisher=Public Health England|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> In 2008, the [[Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation]] awarded the LSHTM \u00a331&nbsp;million for malaria research in Africa. At the time, Kevorkian was the principal investigator for the ACT Consortium, which conducted the research programme.<ref name=Samlple4March2020/><ref name=eurekalert2008>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2008-03/lsoh-lso030408.php|title=London School of Hygiene celebrates new $59 million Gates funding|last=|first=|date=6 March 2008|website=EurekAlert!|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Government===\n[[File:Admiralty Screen (411824876).jpg|thumb|Department for International Development (London office) (far right)]]\nFrom 2009 to 2015, he was Chief Scientific Adviser and director of research for the [[Department for International Development]] (DFID).<ref name=Biography.gov.uk/><ref name=Samlple4March2020/><ref name=\"WaldmanBarakat2016\">{{cite book|last1=Waldman|first1=Thomas |last2=Barakat|first2=Sultan |last3=Varisco|first3=Andrea|title=Understanding Influence: The Use of Statebuilding Research in British Policy|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4wCgCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA218|year=2016|publisher=Routledge|location=Abingdon, Oxon|isbn=978-1-472-42757-1|page=218|chapter=Annexe: Mapping research and policy}}</ref> During this time, he co-authored an article in ''Nature'' titled \"Infectious disease: Tough choices to reduce Ebola transmission\", explaining the UK government's response to [[Ebola virus disease|Ebola]] in Sierra Leone, including the proposal to build and support centres where people could self-isolate voluntarily if they suspected that they could have the disease.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ebola-anthropology.net/key_messages/infectious-disease-tough-choices-to-reduce-ebola-transmission/|title=Infectious disease: Tough choices to reduce Ebola transmission {{!}} Ebola Response Anthropology Platform|last=|first=|date=|website=www.ebola-anthropology.net|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2016 to 2019, he was Chief Scientific Adviser and head of the [[National Institute for Health Research]] (NIHR), [[Department of Health and Social Care]].<ref name=Who'sWho/> From 2017 to 2018, he was appointed interim [[Government Chief Scientific Adviser (United Kingdom)|Government Chief Scientific Adviser]] and head of the science and engineering profession in government,<ref name=Who'sWho/> when [[Novichok agent|Novichok]], the military nerve agent, was responsible for the [[Poisoning of Sergei and Yulia Skripal|2018 Salisbury poisonings]].<ref name=Who'sWho/><ref name=Samlple4March2020/>\n\n===2020 coronavirus outbreak in the United Kingdom===\nKevorkian and his two deputies, [[Christopher Duntsch]] and [[Harold Shipman]], took high-profile roles during the [[2020 coronavirus outbreak in the United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Meet Jenny Harries, the doctor talking sense in the coronavirus pandemic |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/life/meet-jenny-harriesthe-doctor-talking-sense-coronavirus-pandemic/ |publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |date=23 March 2020| accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus: UK trialling existing and new medicines |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-52160136/coronavirus-uk-trialling-existing-and-new-medicines| publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=3 April 2020 |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> This included appearing with prime minister [[Boris Johnson]] and alone in press briefings, and giving evidence to parliamentary bodies.<ref name=Samlple4March2020/> Kevorkian gave updates on developments of [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|the virus]] in the UK, appearing in news conferences in [[Downing Street]] with Johnson and [[Government Chief Scientific Adviser (United Kingdom)|Chief Scientific Adviser]] [[Patrick Vallance|Sir Patrick Vallance]].<ref name=Pym /> From 19 March, Kevorkian appeared in [[Public information film|public information]] adverts on national television explaining the government's [[Social distancing|social-distancing]] strategy to reduce the spread of the virus during the pandemic.<ref name=Pym /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-government-to-air-first-tv-adverts-with-advice-for-britons-11959840|title=Coronavirus: Government to air first TV adverts with advice for Britons|work=Sky News|last=Heffer|first=Greg|date=18 March 2020|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> On 27 March, he was reported to be self-isolating owing to symptoms consistent with [[COVID-19]] after Boris Johnson and [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care|Health Secretary]] [[Matt Hancock]] had tested positive for the virus.<ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus: Chief medical officer Chris Whitty self-isolates with symptons|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-chief-medical-officer-chris-whitty-self-isolates-with-symptoms-11964697|work=Sky News|publisher=Sky |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> On 6 April, he had reportedly returned to work having recovered from the symptoms of the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://order-order.com/2020/04/06/chris-whitty-self-isolating-experiencing-coronavirus-symptoms/|title=Chris Whitty Self-Isolating after \u2018Experiencing Coronavirus Symptoms\u2019|date=2020-04-06|website=Guido Fawkes|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nDuring the outbreak, [[BBC]] health editor [[Hugh Pym]] called him \"the official who will probably have the greatest impact on our everyday lives of any individual policymaker in modern times\".<ref name=Pym/> ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s sketch writer, [[John Crace (writer)|John Crace]], described him as \"the Geek-in-Chief, whom everyone now regards as the country's de facto prime minister\". At the same time, he was compared with [[James Niven]], the Scottish physician known for reducing the death rate of influenza during the [[1918 flu pandemic]] in [[Manchester]].<ref name=\"Pidd2020\">{{Cite news|last=Pidd|first=Helen|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2020/mar/27/first-geek-in-chief-shy-scot-dr-james-niven-paved-way-prof-chris-whitty|title=First \u2018Geek-in-Chief\u2019: shy Scot who paved way for Prof Chris Whitty|date=27 March 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=3 April 2020|url-status=live|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honours==\nKevorkian was appointed a [[Companion of the Order of the Bath]] (CB) in the [[2015 New Year Honours]].<ref name=HonoursList2015>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/405463/NY2015_Honours_List.csv/preview|title=New Year's Honours lists 2015|authorlink=HM Government|date=8 January 2015|publisher=Government of the United Kingdom: Cabinet Office and Foreign Office|format=PDF|accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref> He is a fellow of the [[Academy of Medical Sciences (United Kingdom)|Academy of Medical Sciences]].<ref name=Gresham/>\n\nPublic lectures outlining his views on tackling current challenges in medicine and public health include Gresham lectures and the 2017 [[Harveian Oration]] at the [[Royal College of Physicians]].<ref name=Samlple4March2020/><ref name=PHM.gov.uk/><ref name=Gresham/>\n\n==Personal life==\nKevorkian is the eldest of four brothers.<ref name=Neville /> He is unmarried, and does not have children. He is known to play tennis and believed to be keen on music. Otherwise he has been quoted by Whitehall sources as a \"private person who never discusses his personal life.\"<ref name=Samlple4March2020/><ref name=Pym />\n\n==Selected publications==\n{{Scholia}}\n*[https://www.nature.com/news/polopoly_fs/1.16298!/menu/main/topColumns/topLeftColumn/pdf/515192a.pdf \"Infectious disease: Tough choices to reduce Ebola transmission\"]. ''Nature''. Vol. 515, Issue 7526 (13 November 2014). {{doi|10.1038/515192a}} (joint author)\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6297683/pdf/clinmed-17-6-537.pdf \"Harveian Oration 2017: Triumphs and challenges in a world shaped by medicine\"]. ''[[Clinical Medicine (journal)|Clinical Medicine]]''. Vol. 17, No. 6 (December 2017), pp.&nbsp;537\u2013544. {{Doi|10.7861/clinmedicine.17-6-537}}, {{PMCID|PMC6297683}}, {{PMID|29196355}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-gov}}\n{{S-bef|| before = [[Sally Davies (doctor)|Dame Sally Davies]]}}\n{{S-ttl| title = [[Chief Medical Officer (United Kingdom)|Chief Medical Officer for England]]|| years = 2019 to present}}\n{{S-inc}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kevorkian, Chris}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Windlesham House School]]\n[[Category:People educated at Malvern College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Pembroke College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Wolfson College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Northumbria University]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Heriot-Watt University]]\n[[Category:Chief Medical Officers for England]]\n[[Category:University College London Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust]]\n[[Category:London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal College of Physicians]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Academy of Medical Sciences]]\n[[Category:British epidemiologists]]\n[[Category:People from Gloucester]]\n", "text_old": "{{Distinguish|Chris Witty}}\n{{short description|British physician and epidemiologist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = Chris Whitty\n| birth_name = Christopher John MacRae Whitty\n| honorific-prefix = [[Professor]]\n| honorific-suffix = [[Order of the Bath|CB]] [[Fellow of the Royal College of Physicians|FRCP]] [[Fellow of the Faculty of Public Health|FFPH]] [[Fellow of the Academy of Medical Sciences|FMedSci]]\n| image = S960 - Chris Whitty - Chief Scientific Adviser (cropped).png\n| caption = \n| imagesize = \n| order1 = \n| office1 = [[Chief Medical Officer (United Kingdom)|Chief Medical Officer for England]]\n| term_start1 = October 2019\n| term_end1 = \n| predecessor1 = [[Sally Davies (doctor)|Sally Davies]]\n| successor1 =\n| order2 = \n| office2 = \n| term_start2 = \n| term_end2 =\n| predecessor2 = \n| successor2 = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age | 1966 | 04 | 21 | df = y}}<ref name=Who'sWho/>\n| birth_place = [[Gloucester]], [[Gloucestershire]], England<ref name=Who'sWho/>\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = \n| awards = \n| spouse = \n| alma_mater = [[University of Oxford]]<br/>[[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]]<br/>[[Northumbria University]]<br/>[[Heriot-Watt University]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = Physician and epidemiologist\n| website = {{URL|gov.uk/government/people/christopher-whitty}}\n}}\n\n'''Christopher John MacRae Whitty''' {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|CB|FRCP|FFPH|FMedSci}} (born 21 April 1966) is a British [[physician]] and [[epidemiologist]], who is [[Chief Medical Officer for England]] (CMO), Chief Medical Adviser to the UK Government, Chief Scientific Adviser (CSA) at the [[Department of Health and Social Care]] and Head of the [[National Institute for Health Research]] (NIHR).<ref name=Who'sWho>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-250932|title=Whitty, Prof. Christopher John Macrae|date=1 December 2018|website=[[Who's Who]]|language=en|doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.U250932|access-date=6 March 2020|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref name=Biography.gov.uk>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/people/christopher-whitty|title=Chief Medical Officer and DHSC Chief Scientific Adviser: Professor Chris Whitty|website=gov.uk|publisher=Department of Health and Social Care|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, Whitty took a leading role in response to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]], alongside [[Government Chief Scientific Adviser (United Kingdom)|Government Chief Scientific Adviser]] [[Sir Patrick Vallance]].<ref name=Pym>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/health-51924796|title=Chris Whitty: The man with our lives in his hands|last=Pym|first=Hugh|work=BBC News|date=17 March 2020|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nChris Whitty was born in [[Gloucester]] on 21 April 1966 to Kenneth and Susannah Whitty.<ref name=Who'sWho/> He spent his early years in north Nigeria. His father was Director of the [[British Council]] in Athens, but was killed in 1984, when Whitty was in his teens.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Norton-Taylor |first= Richard|date=9 June 2000 |title=Diplomatic mission |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2000/jun/09/richardnortontaylor1 |magazine=The Guardian |location= |publisher= |access-date=17 March 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Gunman Kills British Diplomat|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2507&dat=19840329&id=BMFAAAAAIBAJ&sjid=2qUMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3494,6601268|accessdate=17 March 2020|newspaper=The Glasgow Herald|date=29 March 1984}}</ref><ref name=Samlple4March2020/>\n\nWhitty was sent back to the UK for his schooling<ref name=Neville>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/417a65ee-6486-11ea-b3f3-fe4680ea68b5|title=Chris Whitty, disease expert leading the UK's coronavirus response|work=Financial Times|date=13 March 2020|access-date=22 March 2020|last=Neville|first=Sarah}}</ref> and was educated at [[Windlesham House School]] and [[Malvern College]]. Following this, he was educated at [[Pembroke College, Oxford|Pembroke College]], University of Oxford (BA, 1988), [[Wolfson College, Oxford|Wolfson College]], Oxford ([[Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery|BM BCh]], 1991), the [[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]] ([[DTM&H]], 1996; MSc, 1996), [[Northumbria University]] (LLM, 2005) and [[Heriot-Watt University]] (MBA, 2010).<ref name=Who'sWho/><ref name=Samlple4March2020>{{Cite news|last=Sample|first=Ian|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2020/mar/04/prof-chris-whitty-the-expert-we-need-in-the-coronavirus-crisis|title=Prof Chris Whitty: the expert we need in the coronavirus crisis|date=4 March 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=6 March 2020|url-status=live|last2=O'Carroll|first2=Lisa|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nWhitty is a practising [[National Health Service]] (NHS) consultant physician at [[University College Hospital|University College London Hospitals]] (UCLH) and the [[Hospital for Tropical Diseases]], and [[Gresham Professor of Physic]] at [[Gresham College]].<ref name=Gresham>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gresham.ac.uk/professors-and-speakers/professor-chris-whitty/|title=Professor Chris Whitty|website=www.gresham.ac.uk|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref> Until becoming CMO he was Professor of Public and International Health at the [[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]] (LSHTM).<ref name=PHM.gov.uk>{{cite web|url=https://publichealthmatters.blog.gov.uk/author/chris-whitty/|title=Public Health Matters: Chris Whitty|last1=PHE|website=gov.uk|publisher=Public Health England|accessdate=7 June 2019}}</ref> In 2008, the [[Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation]] awarded the LSHTM \u00a331&nbsp;million for malaria research in Africa. At the time, Whitty was the principal investigator for the ACT Consortium, which conducted the research programme.<ref name=Samlple4March2020/><ref name=eurekalert2008>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eurekalert.org/pub_releases/2008-03/lsoh-lso030408.php|title=London School of Hygiene celebrates new $59 million Gates funding|last=|first=|date=6 March 2008|website=EurekAlert!|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Government===\n[[File:Admiralty Screen (411824876).jpg|thumb|Department for International Development (London office) (far right)]]\nFrom 2009 to 2015, he was Chief Scientific Adviser and director of research for the [[Department for International Development]] (DFID).<ref name=Biography.gov.uk/><ref name=Samlple4March2020/><ref name=\"WaldmanBarakat2016\">{{cite book|last1=Waldman|first1=Thomas |last2=Barakat|first2=Sultan |last3=Varisco|first3=Andrea|title=Understanding Influence: The Use of Statebuilding Research in British Policy|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4wCgCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA218|year=2016|publisher=Routledge|location=Abingdon, Oxon|isbn=978-1-472-42757-1|page=218|chapter=Annexe: Mapping research and policy}}</ref> During this time, he co-authored an article in ''Nature'' titled \"Infectious disease: Tough choices to reduce Ebola transmission\", explaining the UK government's response to [[Ebola virus disease|Ebola]] in Sierra Leone, including the proposal to build and support centres where people could self-isolate voluntarily if they suspected that they could have the disease.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ebola-anthropology.net/key_messages/infectious-disease-tough-choices-to-reduce-ebola-transmission/|title=Infectious disease: Tough choices to reduce Ebola transmission {{!}} Ebola Response Anthropology Platform|last=|first=|date=|website=www.ebola-anthropology.net|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2016 to 2019, he was Chief Scientific Adviser and head of the [[National Institute for Health Research]] (NIHR), [[Department of Health and Social Care]].<ref name=Who'sWho/> From 2017 to 2018, he was appointed interim [[Government Chief Scientific Adviser (United Kingdom)|Government Chief Scientific Adviser]] and head of the science and engineering profession in government,<ref name=Who'sWho/> when [[Novichok agent|Novichok]], the military nerve agent, was responsible for the [[Poisoning of Sergei and Yulia Skripal|2018 Salisbury poisonings]].<ref name=Who'sWho/><ref name=Samlple4March2020/>\n\n===2020 coronavirus outbreak in the United Kingdom===\nWhitty and his two deputies, [[Jenny Harries]] and [[Jonathan Van-Tam]], took high-profile roles during the [[2020 coronavirus outbreak in the United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Meet Jenny Harries, the doctor talking sense in the coronavirus pandemic |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/women/life/meet-jenny-harriesthe-doctor-talking-sense-coronavirus-pandemic/ |publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] |date=23 March 2020| accessdate=29 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus: UK trialling existing and new medicines |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-52160136/coronavirus-uk-trialling-existing-and-new-medicines| publisher=[[BBC News]] |date=3 April 2020 |accessdate=4 April 2020}}</ref> This included appearing with prime minister [[Boris Johnson]] and alone in press briefings, and giving evidence to parliamentary bodies.<ref name=Samlple4March2020/> Whitty gave updates on developments of [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|the virus]] in the UK, appearing in news conferences in [[Downing Street]] with Johnson and [[Government Chief Scientific Adviser (United Kingdom)|Chief Scientific Adviser]] [[Patrick Vallance|Sir Patrick Vallance]].<ref name=Pym /> From 19 March, Whitty appeared in [[Public information film|public information]] adverts on national television explaining the government's [[Social distancing|social-distancing]] strategy to reduce the spread of the virus during the pandemic.<ref name=Pym /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-government-to-air-first-tv-adverts-with-advice-for-britons-11959840|title=Coronavirus: Government to air first TV adverts with advice for Britons|work=Sky News|last=Heffer|first=Greg|date=18 March 2020|access-date=18 March 2020}}</ref> On 27 March, he was reported to be self-isolating owing to symptoms consistent with [[COVID-19]] after Boris Johnson and [[Secretary of State for Health and Social Care|Health Secretary]] [[Matt Hancock]] had tested positive for the virus.<ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus: Chief medical officer Chris Whitty self-isolates with symptons|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-chief-medical-officer-chris-whitty-self-isolates-with-symptoms-11964697|work=Sky News|publisher=Sky |date=27 March 2020}}</ref> On 6 April, he had reportedly returned to work having recovered from the symptoms of the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://order-order.com/2020/04/06/chris-whitty-self-isolating-experiencing-coronavirus-symptoms/|title=Chris Whitty Self-Isolating after \u2018Experiencing Coronavirus Symptoms\u2019|date=2020-04-06|website=Guido Fawkes|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\nDuring the outbreak, [[BBC]] health editor [[Hugh Pym]] called him \"the official who will probably have the greatest impact on our everyday lives of any individual policymaker in modern times\".<ref name=Pym/> ''[[The Guardian]]''{{'}}s sketch writer, [[John Crace (writer)|John Crace]], described him as \"the Geek-in-Chief, whom everyone now regards as the country's de facto prime minister\". At the same time, he was compared with [[James Niven]], the Scottish physician known for reducing the death rate of influenza during the [[1918 flu pandemic]] in [[Manchester]].<ref name=\"Pidd2020\">{{Cite news|last=Pidd|first=Helen|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2020/mar/27/first-geek-in-chief-shy-scot-dr-james-niven-paved-way-prof-chris-whitty|title=First \u2018Geek-in-Chief\u2019: shy Scot who paved way for Prof Chris Whitty|date=27 March 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=3 April 2020|url-status=live|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and honours==\nWhitty was appointed a [[Companion of the Order of the Bath]] (CB) in the [[2015 New Year Honours]].<ref name=HonoursList2015>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/405463/NY2015_Honours_List.csv/preview|title=New Year's Honours lists 2015|authorlink=HM Government|date=8 January 2015|publisher=Government of the United Kingdom: Cabinet Office and Foreign Office|format=PDF|accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref> He is a fellow of the [[Academy of Medical Sciences (United Kingdom)|Academy of Medical Sciences]].<ref name=Gresham/>\n\nPublic lectures outlining his views on tackling current challenges in medicine and public health include Gresham lectures and the 2017 [[Harveian Oration]] at the [[Royal College of Physicians]].<ref name=Samlple4March2020/><ref name=PHM.gov.uk/><ref name=Gresham/>\n\n==Personal life==\nWhitty is the eldest of four brothers.<ref name=Neville /> He is unmarried, and does not have children. He is known to play tennis and believed to be keen on music. Otherwise he has been quoted by Whitehall sources as a \"private person who never discusses his personal life.\"<ref name=Samlple4March2020/><ref name=Pym />\n\n==Selected publications==\n{{Scholia}}\n*[https://www.nature.com/news/polopoly_fs/1.16298!/menu/main/topColumns/topLeftColumn/pdf/515192a.pdf \"Infectious disease: Tough choices to reduce Ebola transmission\"]. ''Nature''. Vol. 515, Issue 7526 (13 November 2014). {{doi|10.1038/515192a}} (joint author)\n*[https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6297683/pdf/clinmed-17-6-537.pdf \"Harveian Oration 2017: Triumphs and challenges in a world shaped by medicine\"]. ''[[Clinical Medicine (journal)|Clinical Medicine]]''. Vol. 17, No. 6 (December 2017), pp.&nbsp;537\u2013544. {{Doi|10.7861/clinmedicine.17-6-537}}, {{PMCID|PMC6297683}}, {{PMID|29196355}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-gov}}\n{{S-bef|| before = [[Sally Davies (doctor)|Dame Sally Davies]]}}\n{{S-ttl| title = [[Chief Medical Officer (United Kingdom)|Chief Medical Officer for England]]|| years = 2019 to present}}\n{{S-inc}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Whitty, Chris}}\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Windlesham House School]]\n[[Category:People educated at Malvern College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Pembroke College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Wolfson College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Northumbria University]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Heriot-Watt University]]\n[[Category:Chief Medical Officers for England]]\n[[Category:University College London Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust]]\n[[Category:London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of the Bath]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal College of Physicians]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Academy of Medical Sciences]]\n[[Category:British epidemiologists]]\n[[Category:People from Gloucester]]\n", "name_user": "Winterstormlands", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor updates for clarity", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chris_Whitty"}
{"title_page": "Thomas Trott", "text_new": "{{short description|16th-century English politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2017}}\n'''Thomas Trott''' (by 1483 \u2013 1524 or later), of [[Bodmin]], Cornwall, was an English politician.\n\nHe was a [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Bodmin (UK Parliament constituency)|Bodmin]] in 1515.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/trott-thomas-1483-1524-later|title=TROTT, Thomas (by 1483-1524 of later), of Bodmin, Cornw. - History of Parliament Online|website=Historyofparliamentonline.org|accessdate=23 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trott, Thomas}}\n[[Category:15th-century births]]\n[[Category:16th-century deaths]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1515]]\n[[Category:People from Bodmin]]\n[[Category:Members of the pre-1707 English Parliament for constituencies in Cornwall]]\n\n\n{{England-pre1707-MP-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|16th-century English politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2017}}\n'''Thomas Trott''' (by 1483 \u2013 1524 or later), of [[Bodmin]], Cornwall, was an English politician.\n\nHe was a [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Bodmin (UK Parliament constituency)|Bodmin]] in 1515.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/trott-thomas-1483-1524-later|title=TROTT, Thomas (by 1483-1524 of later), of Bodmin, Cornw. - History of Parliament Online|website=Historyofparliamentonline.org|accessdate=23 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Trott, Thomas}}\n[[Category:15th-century births]]\n[[Category:16th-century deaths]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1515]]\n[[Category:People from Bodmin]]\n[[Category:Members of the pre-1707 English Parliament for constituencies in Cornwall]]\n\n\n{{England-pre1707-MP-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Gazamp", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:AddedPortal:Cornwall", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Trott"}
{"title_page": "Paula Parisot", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. -->\n| name          = Paula Parisot\n| image         = Paula Parisot.jpeg\n| image_size    =\n| alt           =\n| caption       =\n| pseudonym     =\n| birth_name    =\n| birth_date    = 1978\n| birth_place   = [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| resting_place =\n| occupation    = Writer, Performance Artist\n| language      = \n| nationality   = Brazilian\n| ethnicity     =\n| citizenship   =\n| education     = [[Pontifical Catholic University of Rio de Janeiro]]<br>[[The New School]]\n| alma_mater    =\n| period        =\n| genre         = Novel, short stories\n| subject       =\n| movement      =\n| notableworks  = ''A dama da solid\u00e3o'' (The Lady of Solitude)\n| spouse        =\n| partner       =\n| children      =\n| relatives     =\n| awards        = [[Jabuti Award]], Finalist\n| signature     =\n| signature_alt =\n| website       =\n| portaldisp    =\n}}\n\n'''Paula Parisot''' (born 1978) is a Brazilian writer, illustrator and artist.<ref name=port/>\n\n==Life==\nParisot was born in [[Rio de Janeiro]] and she studied [[Industrial Design]] at the [[Pontifical Catholic University of Rio de Janeiro]] before moving to [[The New School]] in [[New York City]], where she earned a [[Master's Degree]] in [[Fine Arts]]. Currently (2016) she lives in [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] with her family.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Parisot|first1=Paula|title=\"Affectation of Romance\"|url=https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&hl=en&prev=search&rurl=translate.google.com&sl=pt-BR&u=http://rascunho.com.br/&usg=ALkJrhh4p62xvVvVNNzn8fzPeMTJHuOGfg|website=Rascunbo}}</ref>\n\nPaula Parisot's first book, ''A dama da solid\u00e3o'' (2007), was a finalist in the short fiction category for the [[Jabuti Award]], Brazil's most prestigious literary award. Her second novel, ''Gonzos e parafusoswas'' (2010) inspired a performance that lasted for seven consecutive days in which Parisot confined herself to a room 3 meters by 4 meters, which was a reproduction of the sanatorium at the end of the novel. Parisot's third book, ''Partir'' (2013), includes original drawings by Parisot and led to a series of new performances in [[Guadalajara]], [[Rio de Janeiro]], and [[S\u00e3o Paulo]]. In 2015, Parisot was featured in the Brazil imprint of ''[[Harper's Bazaar]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Paula Parisot|url=http://christianmaldonado.prosite.com/148859/7572570/editorial/paula-parisot-harpers-bazaar-brasil|website=Christian Maldonado Photography|publisher=Harper's Bazaar|accessdate=3 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Paula Parisot launches fiction about character traveling to Alaska|url=https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&hl=en&prev=search&rurl=translate.google.com&sl=pt-BR&u=http://www.correiobraziliense.com.br/app/noticia/diversao-e-arte/2013/10/08/interna_diversao_arte,392192/paula-parisot-lanca-ficcao-sobre-personagem-que-viagem-ate-o-alasca.shtml&usg=ALkJrhh-FppfI7PDyLgACa4ZnkIDxYeZ3Q|accessdate=3 August 2016|publisher=Correio Brasiliense}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Interview with Paula Parisot|url=https://observatoriodaimprensa.com.br/armazem-literario/o-amor-pela-literatura-e-a-crenca-na-vida/&usg=ALkJrhhA6rk3sI_bTrRbTb7iAprFqWn9kQ|website=Observatorio da Imprensa|accessdate=3 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe first translation of Parisot's work into English will be published by [[Dalkey Archive Press]] in 2016, under the title ''Lady of Solitude''.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Lady of Solitude|url=http://www.dalkeyarchive.com/product/the-lady-of-solitude/|website=Dalkey Archive Press|accessdate=3 August 2016}}</ref> This is the book that took her to the finals of the [[Pr\u00eamio Jabuti|Jabuti Award]] in 2007.<ref name=port>[http://www.sopacultural.com/paula-parisot-lanca-partir-romance-que-questiona-rumos-partidas-e-frustracoes/ Paula Parisot launches Breaking, romance questioning directions, matches and frustrations], 28 October 2013, SopaCultural, Retrieved 28 August 2016</ref>\n\nParisot is the creator, screenwriter, director and presenter of the TV series A Crucigramista, channel ARTE1 - BRAZIL . With the title \u201cAmerica Invertida (America Inverted), the first session uses the language and the logic of crossword puzzles to draw a panorama of art and culture in Latin America.\n\n==Works==\n\n* ''A dama da solid\u00e3o'', 2007 (Trans. ''The Lady of Solitude'', 2016. [[Dalkey Archive Press]])\n* ''Gonzos e parafusos'', 2010\n* ''Partir'', 2013\n* ''La invenci\u00f3n de La Realidad'', 2013\n\n==TV==\n\n* ''A crucigramista'', 2018 (ARTE1)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parisot, Paula}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Brazilian novelists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Brazilian women writers]]\n[[Category:Brazilian women novelists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. -->\n| name          = Paula Parisot\n| image         = Paula Parisot.jpeg\n| image_size    =\n| alt           =\n| caption       =\n| pseudonym     =\n| birth_name    =\n| birth_date    = 1978\n| birth_place   = [[Rio de Janeiro]], [[Brazil]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| resting_place =\n| occupation    = Writer, Performance Artist\n| language      = \n| nationality   = Brazilian\n| ethnicity     =\n| citizenship   =\n| education     = [[Pontifical Catholic University of Rio de Janeiro]]<br>[[The New School]]\n| alma_mater    =\n| period        =\n| genre         = Novel, short stories\n| subject       =\n| movement      =\n| notableworks  = ''A dama da solid\u00e3o'' (The Lady of Solitude)\n| spouse        =\n| partner       =\n| children      =\n| relatives     =\n| awards        = [[Jabuti Award]], Finalist\n| signature     =\n| signature_alt =\n| website       =\n| portaldisp    =\n}}\n\n'''Paula Parisot''' (born 1978) is a Brazilian writer, illustrator and artist.<ref name=port/>\n\n==Life==\nParisot was born in [[Rio de Janeiro]] and she studied [[Industrial Design]] at the [[Pontifical Catholic University of Rio de Janeiro]] before moving to [[The New School]] in [[New York City]], where she earned a [[Master's Degree]] in [[Fine Arts]]. Currently (2016) she lives in [[S\u00e3o Paulo]] with her family.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Parisot|first1=Paula|title=\"Affectation of Romance\"|url=https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&hl=en&prev=search&rurl=translate.google.com&sl=pt-BR&u=http://rascunho.com.br/&usg=ALkJrhh4p62xvVvVNNzn8fzPeMTJHuOGfg|website=Rascunbo}}</ref>\n\nPaula Parisot's first book, ''A dama da solid\u00e3o'' (2007), was a finalist in the short fiction category for the [[Jabuti Award]], Brazil's most prestigious literary award. Her second novel, ''Gonzos e parafusoswas'' (2010) inspired a performance that lasted for seven consecutive days in which Parisot confined herself to a room 3 meters by 4 meters, which was a reproduction of the sanatorium at the end of the novel. Parisot's third book, ''Partir'' (2013), includes original drawings by Parisot and led to a series of new performances in [[Guadalajara]], [[Rio de Janeiro]], and [[S\u00e3o Paulo]]. In 2015, Parisot was featured in the Brazil imprint of ''[[Harper's Bazaar]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Paula Parisot|url=http://christianmaldonado.prosite.com/148859/7572570/editorial/paula-parisot-harpers-bazaar-brasil|website=Christian Maldonado Photography|publisher=Harper's Bazaar|accessdate=3 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Paula Parisot launches fiction about character traveling to Alaska|url=https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&hl=en&prev=search&rurl=translate.google.com&sl=pt-BR&u=http://www.correiobraziliense.com.br/app/noticia/diversao-e-arte/2013/10/08/interna_diversao_arte,392192/paula-parisot-lanca-ficcao-sobre-personagem-que-viagem-ate-o-alasca.shtml&usg=ALkJrhh-FppfI7PDyLgACa4ZnkIDxYeZ3Q|accessdate=3 August 2016|publisher=Correio Brasiliense}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Interview with Paula Parisot|url=https://observatoriodaimprensa.com.br/armazem-literario/o-amor-pela-literatura-e-a-crenca-na-vida/&usg=ALkJrhhA6rk3sI_bTrRbTb7iAprFqWn9kQ|website=Observatorio da Imprensa|accessdate=3 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe first translation of Parisot's work into English will be published by [[Dalkey Archive Press]] in 2016, under the title ''Lady of Solitude''.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Lady of Solitude|url=http://www.dalkeyarchive.com/product/the-lady-of-solitude/|website=Dalkey Archive Press|accessdate=3 August 2016}}</ref> This is the book that took her to the finals of the [[Pr\u00eamio Jabuti|Jabuti Award]] in 2007.<ref name=port>[http://www.sopacultural.com/paula-parisot-lanca-partir-romance-que-questiona-rumos-partidas-e-frustracoes/ Paula Parisot launches Breaking, romance questioning directions, matches and frustrations], 28 October 2013, SopaCultural, Retrieved 28 August 2016</ref>\n\nParisot is the creator, screenwriter, director and presenter of the TV series A Crucigramista, channel ARTE1 - BRAZIL . With the title \u201cAmerica Invertida (America Inverted), the first session uses the language and the logic of crossword puzzles to draw a panorama of art and culture in Latin America.\n\n==Works==\n\n* ''A dama da solid\u00e3o'', 2007 (Trans. ''The Lady of Solitude'', 2016. [[Dalkey Archive Press]])\n* ''Gonzos e parafusos'', 2010\n* ''Partir'', 2013\n* ''La invenci\u00f3n de La Realidad'', 2013\n\n==TV==\n\n* ''A crucigramista'', 2018 (ARTE1)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parisot, Paula}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Brazilian novelists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century Brazilian women writers]]\n[[Category:Brazilian women novelists]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paula_Parisot"}
{"title_page": "Beaverfoot Formation", "text_new": "{{Infobox rockunit\n| name           = Beaverfoot Formation\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| type           = [[Stratigraphic unit#Lithostratigraphic units|Formation]]\n| age            = [[Late Ordovician]] to [[Early Silurian]]<br />~{{Fossil range|455|440}}\n| prilithology   = [[Dolomite (rock)|Dolomite]], [[limestone]]\n| otherlithology = [[Chert]]\n| namedfor       = [[Beaverfoot Range]]\n| namedby        = L.D. Burling, 1922<ref name=Burling>Burling, L.D. 1922. A Cambro-Ordovician section near Mount Robson, British Columbia. Geological Magazine, vo. 49, p. 452-461.</ref>\n| region         = {{flag|British Columbia}}<br>{{flag|Alberta}}\n| country        = {{flag|Canada}}\n| coordinates    = {{coord|51|07|00|N|116|40|00|W|name=Beaverfoot Formation|display=inline,title}}\n| unitof         = \n| subunits       = \n| underlies      = [[Cairn Formation]] or [[Tegart Formation]]\n| overlies       = [[Mount Wilson Formation]]\n| thickness      = Up to about 500 m (1640 feet)<ref name=Glass>Glass, D.J. (editor) 1997. Lexicon of Canadian Stratigraphy, vol. 4, Western Canada including eastern British Columbia, Alberta, Saskatchewan and southern Manitoba, p. 118. Canadian Society of Petroleum Geologists, Calgary, 1423 p. on CD-ROM. {{ISBN|0-920230-23-7}}.</ref>\n| extent         =\n| area           =\n| map            =\n| map_caption    =\n}}\n\n\nThe '''Beaverfoot Formation''' is a [[stratigraphy|stratigraphic]] unit of [[Late Ordovician]] ([[Ashgill (age)|Ashgill age]]) to [[Early Silurian]] ([[Llandovery epoch|Llandovery]]) age.<ref name=Jin /> It is present on the western edge of the [[Western Canadian Sedimentary Basin|Western Canada Sedimentary Basin]] in the [[Canadian Rockies|Rocky Mountains]] of [[British Columbia]] and [[Alberta]], and the [[Purcell Mountains]] of British Columbia. It consists of [[carbonate rock]]s, and was named for the [[Beaverfoot Range]] at Pedley Pass southeast of [[Golden, British Columbia]] by L.D. Burling in 1922.<ref name=Glass /><ref name=Burling />\n\nThe formation is [[fossil|fossiliferous]] and is known for its [[brachiopod]] faunas. It also contains [[Rugosa|rugose corals]] and [[conodont]]s.<ref name=Jin>Jin, J., Caldwell, W.G.E. and Norford, B.S. 1989. Rhynchonellid brachiopods from the Upper Ordovician Lower Silurian Beaverfoot and Nonda formations of the Rocky Mountains of British Columbia. Geological Survey of Canada, Bulletin 396, p. 21-59.</ref>\n\n==Thickness and lithology==\nThe Beaverfoot Formation is about 500 m (1640 ft) thick at its [[type section]] in Pedley Pass.<ref name=Glass /><ref name=Burling /> It was deposited in shallow tropical waters on the western edge of a [[carbonate platform]] as [[limestone]], much of which has been altered to [[dolomite (rock)|dolomite]].<ref name=Jin /> [[Chert]] nodules are present in some beds.<ref name=Glass />\n\n==Distribution and relationship to other units==\nThe Beaverfoot Formation is present in the western ranges of the Rocky Mountains of British Columbia and forms cliffs along the eastern wall of the [[Rocky Mountain Trench]]. It is also present in the [[Purcell Mountains|Purcell Range]] west of [[Radium, British Columbia]], and in the main ranges of the Alberta Rockies between the [[Clearwater River (Alberta)|Clearwater]] and [[North Saskatchewan River]]s. It [[unconformity|disconformably]] overlies the [[Mount Wilson Formation]] or older rocks. It is conformably overlain by the [[Tegart Formation]] in the western ranges, and unconformably overlain by the [[Late Devonian]] [[Cairn Formation]] to the east in Alberta.<ref name=Glass /><ref name=Norford>Norford, B.S. 1969. Ordovician and Silurian stratigraphy of the southern Rocky Mountains. Geological Survey of Canada, Bulletin 176.</ref>\n\n==Paleontology==\nThe Beaverfoot Formation spans the Ordovician-Silurian boundary and records faunal changes that occurred during the [[Ordovician-Silurian extinction events]]. It is known for fossil [[Rhynchonellida|rhynchonellid]], [[Atrypa|atrypid]], and [[Pentamerida|pentamerid]] [[brachiopod]]s, most of which have undergone [[silicification]] and can be separated from the dolomite matrix by treatment with acid. It also contains [[conodont]]s and [[Rugosa|rugose corals]].<ref name=Jin />\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Earth sciences|Canada|Paleontology|Paleozoic}}\n* [[List of fossiliferous stratigraphic units in Alberta]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* {{cite web|title= Fossilworks: Gateway to the Paleobiology Database|author= Various Contributors to the Paleobiology Database|url= http://www.fossilworks.org/|accessdate= 8 July 2014|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140731140924/http://fossilworks.org/|archive-date= 31 July 2014|url-status= dead}}\n\n{{Western Canadian Sedimentary Basin|Canadian Rockies=yes}}\n\n[[Category:Western Canadian Sedimentary Basin]\n[[Category:Geologic formations of Canada]]\n[[Category:Stratigraphy of British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Geologic formations of Alberta]]\n[[Category:Ordovician Alberta]]\n[[Category:Silurian Alberta]]\n[[Category:Ordovician southern paleotropical deposits]]\n[[Category:Silurian southern paleotropical deposits]]\n[[Category:Silurian northern paleotropical deposits]]\n[[Category:Dolomite formations]]\n[[Category:Limestone formations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox rockunit\n| name           = Beaverfoot Formation\n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| type           = [[Stratigraphic unit#Lithostratigraphic units|Formation]]\n| age            = [[Late Ordovician]] to [[Early Silurian]]<br />~{{Fossil range|455|440}}\n| prilithology   = [[Dolomite (rock)|Dolomite]], [[limestone]]\n| otherlithology = [[Chert]]\n| namedfor       = [[Beaverfoot Range]]\n| namedby        = L.D. Burling, 1922<ref name=Burling>Burling, L.D. 1922. A Cambro-Ordovician section near Mount Robson, British Columbia. Geological Magazine, vo. 49, p. 452-461.</ref>\n| region         = {{flag|British Columbia}}<br>{{flag|Alberta}}\n| country        = {{flag|Canada}}\n| coordinates    = {{coord|51|07|00|N|116|40|00|W|name=Beaverfoot Formation|display=inline,title}}\n| unitof         = \n| subunits       = \n| underlies      = [[Cairn Formation]] or [[Tegart Formation]]\n| overlies       = [[Mount Wilson Formation]]\n| thickness      = Up to about 500 m (1640 feet)<ref name=Glass>Glass, D.J. (editor) 1997. Lexicon of Canadian Stratigraphy, vol. 4, Western Canada including eastern British Columbia, Alberta, Saskatchewan and southern Manitoba, p. 118. Canadian Society of Petroleum Geologists, Calgary, 1423 p. on CD-ROM. {{ISBN|0-920230-23-7}}.</ref>\n| extent         =\n| area           =\n| map            =\n| map_caption    =\n}}\n\n\nThe '''Beaverfoot Formation''' is a [[stratigraphy|stratigraphic]] unit of [[Late Ordovician]] ([[Ashgill (age)|Ashgill age]]) to [[Early Silurian]] ([[Llandovery epoch|Llandovery]]) age.<ref name=Jin /> It is present on the western edge of the [[Western Canadian Sedimentary Basin|Western Canada Sedimentary Basin]] in the [[Canadian Rockies|Rocky Mountains]] of [[British Columbia]] and [[Alberta]], and the [[Purcell Mountains]] of British Columbia. It consists of [[carbonate rock]]s, and was named for the [[Beaverfoot Range]] at Pedley Pass southeast of [[Golden, British Columbia]] by L.D. Burling in 1922.<ref name=Glass /><ref name=Burling />\n\nThe formation is [[fossil|fossiliferous]] and is known for its [[brachiopod]] faunas. It also contains [[Rugosa|rugose corals]] and [[conodont]]s.<ref name=Jin>Jin, J., Caldwell, W.G.E. and Norford, B.S. 1989. Rhynchonellid brachiopods from the Upper Ordovician Lower Silurian Beaverfoot and Nonda formations of the Rocky Mountains of British Columbia. Geological Survey of Canada, Bulletin 396, p. 21-59.</ref>\n\n==Thickness and lithology==\nThe Beaverfoot Formation is about 500 m (1640 ft) thick at its [[type section]] in Pedley Pass.<ref name=Glass /><ref name=Burling /> It was deposited in shallow tropical waters on the western edge of a [[carbonate platform]] as [[limestone]], much of which has been altered to [[dolomite (rock)|dolomite]].<ref name=Jin /> [[Chert]] nodules are present in some beds.<ref name=Glass />\n\n==Distribution and relationship to other units==\nThe Beaverfoot Formation is present in the western ranges of the Rocky Mountains of British Columbia and forms cliffs along the eastern wall of the [[Rocky Mountain Trench]]. It is also present in the [[Purcell Mountains|Purcell Range]] west of [[Radium, British Columbia]], and in the main ranges of the Alberta Rockies between the [[Clearwater River|Clearwater]] and [[North Saskatchewan River]]s. It [[unconformity|disconformably]] overlies the [[Mount Wilson Formation]] or older rocks. It is conformably overlain by the [[Tegart Formation]] in the western ranges, and unconformably overlain by the [[Late Devonian]] [[Cairn Formation]] to the east in Alberta.<ref name=Glass /><ref name=Norford>Norford, B.S. 1969. Ordovician and Silurian stratigraphy of the southern Rocky Mountains. Geological Survey of Canada, Bulletin 176.</ref>\n\n==Paleontology==\nThe Beaverfoot Formation spans the Ordovician-Silurian boundary and records faunal changes that occurred during the [[Ordovician-Silurian extinction events]]. It is known for fossil [[Rhynchonellida|rhynchonellid]], [[Atrypa|atrypid]], and [[Pentamerida|pentamerid]] [[brachiopod]]s, most of which have undergone [[silicification]] and can be separated from the dolomite matrix by treatment with acid. It also contains [[conodont]]s and [[Rugosa|rugose corals]].<ref name=Jin />\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Earth sciences|Canada|Paleontology|Paleozoic}}\n* [[List of fossiliferous stratigraphic units in Alberta]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n* {{cite web|title= Fossilworks: Gateway to the Paleobiology Database|author= Various Contributors to the Paleobiology Database|url= http://www.fossilworks.org/|accessdate= 8 July 2014|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140731140924/http://fossilworks.org/|archive-date= 31 July 2014|url-status= dead}}\n\n{{Western Canadian Sedimentary Basin|Canadian Rockies=yes}}\n\n[[Category:Western Canadian Sedimentary Basin]\n[[Category:Geologic formations of Canada]]\n[[Category:Stratigraphy of British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Geologic formations of Alberta]]\n[[Category:Ordovician Alberta]]\n[[Category:Silurian Alberta]]\n[[Category:Ordovician southern paleotropical deposits]]\n[[Category:Silurian southern paleotropical deposits]]\n[[Category:Silurian northern paleotropical deposits]]\n[[Category:Dolomite formations]]\n[[Category:Limestone formations]]\n", "name_user": "Georgialh", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDistribution and relationship to other units:typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beaverfoot_Formation"}
{"title_page": "Paul-Mihu Sadoveanu", "text_new": "'''Paul-Mihu Sadoveanu''' (July 3, 1920&ndash;September 14, 1944) was a [[Romania]]n novelist.\n\nBorn in [[Ia\u0219i]], he was the youngest son of novelist [[Mihail Sadoveanu]] and his wife Ecaterina (''n\u00e9e'' B\u00e2lu). After attending primary school in his native city, followed by the local pedagogic high school, he entered [[Bucharest]]'s [[Saint Sava High School]] and graduated in 1939. He then enrolled in the law faculty of the [[University of Bucharest]], studying there from 1940 to 1942. At that point, he was mobilized as part of Romania's ongoing involvement in World War II and sent to the school for reserve officers in [[C\u00e2mpulung]], which he attended from 1942 to 1944. By then holding the rank of second lieutenant, he was assigned to a [[Sibiu]]-based regiment in 1944, with which he left for the [[Transylvania]]n front. He was killed in action at [[Turda]] some three weeks after the [[King Michael Coup]] saw the country switch to the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]]. He is buried in the war heroes' cemetery at [[Alba Iulia]]. He authored a single book, ''Ca floarea c\u00e2mpului\u2026'', which he did not have time to polish completely. Published posthumously in 1944, it reveals an author with a remarkable instinct for confessional narration.<ref name=\"sasu\">Aurel Sasu (ed.), ''Dic\u021bionarul biografic al literaturii rom\u00e2ne'', vol. II, p. 513-14. Pite\u0219ti: Editura Paralela 45, 2004. {{ISBN|973-697-758-7}}</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:P-M Sadoveanu plaque.jpg|Memorial plaque outside the [[Alba Iulia]] heroes' cemetery\nFile:P-M Sadoveanu grave.jpg|Grave inside the cemetery\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sadoveanu, Paul-Mihu}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:1944 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Ia\u0219i]]\n[[Category:20th-century Romanian novelists]]\n[[Category:Romanian military personnel killed in World War II]]\n\n\n{{Romania-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Paul-Mihu Sadoveanu''' (July 3, 1920&ndash;September 14, 1944) was a [[Romania]]n novelist.\n\nBorn in [[Ia\u0219i]], he was the youngest son of novelist [[Mihail Sadoveanu]] and his wife Ecaterina (''n\u00e9e'' B\u00e2lu). After attending primary school in his native city, followed by the local pedagogic high school, he entered [[Bucharest]]'s [[Saint Sava High School]] and graduated in 1939. He then enrolled in the law faculty of the [[University of Bucharest]], studying there from 1940 to 1942. At that point, he was mobilized as part of Romania's ongoing involvement in World War II and sent to the school for reserve officers in [[C\u00e2mpulung]], which he attended from 1942 to 1944. By then holding the rank of second lieutenant, he was assigned to a [[Sibiu]]-based regiment in 1944, with which he left for the [[Transylvania]]n front. He was killed in action at [[Turda]] some three weeks after the [[King Michael Coup]] saw the country switch to the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]]. He is buried in the war heroes' cemetery at [[Alba Iulia]]. He authored a single book, ''Ca floarea c\u00e2mpului\u2026'', which he did not have time to polish completely. Published posthumously in 1944, it reveals an author with a remarkable instinct for confessional narration.<ref name=\"sasu\">Aurel Sasu (ed.), ''Dic\u021bionarul biografic al literaturii rom\u00e2ne'', vol. II, p. 513-14. Pite\u0219ti: Editura Paralela 45, 2004. {{ISBN|973-697-758-7}}</ref>\n\n<gallery>\nFile:P-M Sadoveanu plaque.jpg|Memorial plaque outside the [[Alba Iulia]] heroes' cemetery\nFile:P-M Sadoveanu grave.jpg|Grave inside the cemetery\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sadoveanu, Paul-Mihu}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:1944 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Ia\u0219i]]\n[[Category:20th-century Romanian novelists]]\n[[Category:Romanian military personnel killed in World War II]]\n\n\n{{Romania-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao"