{"title_page": "Paul Wheeler (writer)", "text_new": "{{Unreliable sources|date=October 2019}}\n'''Paul Wheeler''' (born 1934) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[screenwriter]] and novelist. He was born in 1934 in [[Kingston, Jamaica|Kingston]], [[Jamaica]]. He obtained his BA from [[Exeter College, Oxford]] in 1959 and his MA from the [[University of Chicago]] in 1960.\n\nAs a screenwriter, he is best known for his scripts for ''The Medallion'' (2003), ''[[Caravan to Vaccares]]'' (1974) and ''The Terrorists'' (1975). He also wrote scripts for numerous TV series like ''[[Tenko (TV series)|Tenko]]'', ''[[Minder]]'' and ''[[Poldark]]''. In the early 1980s, he published a novel on the [[Bodyline controversy]], which was adapted as an [[Australian]] TV series starring [[Hugo Weaving]].\n\nHe married Alexandra Martinez in 1964. He is related by marriage to the American journalist [[Morton Kondracke]].<ref>[https://www.unitedagents.co.uk/cv/10032/film_tv_theatre CV]</ref><ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0923932/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm IMDb profile]</ref><ref>''Science Fiction and Fantasy Literature, Volume 2'' by R. Reginald, Mary A. Burgess, Douglas Menville</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:British writers]]\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Exeter College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Unreliable sources|date=October 2019}}\n'''Paul Wheeler''' (born 1934) is a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[screenwriter]] and novelist. He was born in 1934 in [[Kingston, Jamaica|Kingston]], [[Jamaica]]. He obtained his BA from [[Exeter College, Oxford]] in 1959 and his MA from the [[University of Chicago]] in 1960. \n\nAs a screenwriter, he is best known for his scripts for ''The Medallion'' (2003), ''[[Caravan to Vaccares]]'' (1974) and ''The Terrorists'' (1975). He also wrote scripts for numerous TV series like ''[[Tenko (TV series)|Tenko]]'', ''[[Minder]]'' and ''[[Poldark]]''. In the early 1980s, he published a novel on the [[Bodyline controversy]], which was adapted as an [[Australian]] TV series starring [[Hugo Weaving]].\n\nHe married Alexandra Martinez in 1964. He is related by marriage to the American journalist [[Morton Kondracke]].<ref>[https://www.unitedagents.co.uk/cv/10032/film_tv_theatre CV]</ref><ref>[https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0923932/bio?ref_=nm_ov_bio_sm IMDb profile]</ref><ref>''Science Fiction and Fantasy Literature, Volume 2'' by R. Reginald, Mary A. Burgess, Douglas Menville</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[category:British writers]]\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Exeter College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:University of Chicago alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Wheeler_(writer)"}
